He was speaking to BBC Focus on Africa in his first interview since his opponent, Peter Mutharika, was announced the winner of the presidential race. He added that he did not attend Mutharika's swearing in earlier on Tuesday because he had not been invited. Chakwera, the leader of the Malawi Congress Party, insists there is still a case to be heard in the courts. "If we do not fight for the Malawians they may never know what actually happened," he said. He argued that there had been serious irregularities in the counting of the vote. “It’s an electoral system in which officers of the electoral commission can use correction fluid on results sheets from all over the country... and yet there are no consequences,” he said. Mutharika has rejected criticism of the election result, saying international observers had given the vote a clean bill of health. --BBC--